      {
        "id": "6a1678ce55da224da4a4db6cb5d63f98d779682d",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 2065,
          "name": "Yuli Shlosberg",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "ys9693@att.com",
          "username": "ys9693"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2020-02-24 14:35:58.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1\n\nWe have carefully reviewed this commit and found that the way of implementation conflicts the following core design architecture.\nWe would like to preserve basic artifact types (e.g. HEAT, HEAT_ENV etc.) and leave it as a constant and hard-coded ( meaning using ENUMS) \n\nThe reasons for above architecture are:\n 1. making better performance by avoid strings comparison\n 2. making sure that any SDC environment is aligned and minimally supports core artifact types.\n\nThis will allow us to export/import services between different SDC env.\n\nThe solution that we would like to suggest is to use custom artifact types, that will be provided from configuration, and will extend the basic artifact core types.",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "b9447a15fa83610e78980f424c805477cb5c7760",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 5565,
          "name": "Andr� Schmid",
          "display_name": "André Schmid",
          "email": "andre.schmid@est.tech",
          "username": "andre.schmid"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2020-02-24 14:53:24.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\n> Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1\n> \n> We have carefully reviewed this commit and found that the way of implementation conflicts the following core design architecture.\n> We would like to preserve basic artifact types (e.g. HEAT, HEAT_ENV etc.) and leave it as a constant and hard-coded ( meaning using ENUMS) \n> \n> The reasons for above architecture are:\n>  1. making better performance by avoid strings comparison\n>  2. making sure that any SDC environment is aligned and minimally supports core artifact types.\n> \n> This will allow us to export/import services between different SDC env.\n> \n> The solution that we would like to suggest is to use custom artifact types, that will be provided from configuration, and will extend the basic artifact core types.\n\nHi Yuli,\n\nThanks for the analysis.\n\nMy main question is: Why do SDC have a configuration file for the Artifacts types if the idea is to be hard coded?\n\nPerformance wise, I don't see big difference, as is frequently needed to parse the string type to the Enum type. Probably the String comparison is quicker than that.\n\nWe can continue to discuss in the Jira to achieve a good solution, I will leave my comment there.",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "60b69ae528724616de712f58907b5e561652096e",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 5269,
          "name": "Michael Morris",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "michael.morris@est.tech",
          "username": "MichaelMorris"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2020-02-24 15:25:44.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nIt is not likely that services exported from SDC in one operators deployment will be imported in the SDC deployment of another operator. Why then would there be a need to align between all deployments. \nWe are not proposing to change or remove any of the existing core artifact types, which will continue to be aligned. We are only seeking to allow additional artifact types for which support will be desired in some deployments. \nThis will allow the flexibility to include artifacts that may be required by a component in one system that is not used in other systems.\nIt is an acceptable and understandable limitation on this customization that export/import will only be supported across deployments with the same configuration of artifact types.",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "b0ed48ce783a9cf374fc4239f247fb45c008535a",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 5269,
          "name": "Michael Morris",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "michael.morris@est.tech",
          "username": "MichaelMorris"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2020-02-28 08:43:22.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nHi Yuli, have you had a chance to consider our above responses to your comments",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
